snippet.textDisplay: I lived in a flat in Mumbai with three great, talented guys, all from different cities. We were pretty much always broke, we were nobodies and we were starting out. This pretty much became the anthem of the house. 4 unmarried guys in their mid-twenties would endlessly listen to a song about a 'ghar'...those lyrics..my my..dono rahenge kabutar se...rahon konrahein batayenge saathi hum, aisa hoga safar...and most outstandingl for someone jisko Mumbai raas aa gayi hai...ujla hi ujla sheher hoga, jisme hum tum banayenge ghar! I have a house now and funny that I am listening to this song the day I am ending something I have with a girl. I love the spirit of Mumbai! Jai Ho!

snippet.textDisplay:
We've gotta thank coke studio for bringing these beautiful compositions to life, which would otherwise be unheard of in this day and age of commercial music composed solely for movies, catering to mainstream audience.

If it were the 80s-90s, Piyush Mishra could've released songs like Ghar and Husna on his own album, the age when we had our very own Indi-pop, and albums which had an identity, composed without any inhibitions.
